# {{.Name}} ({{.Type}})

{{ .Description | trimspace }}

A bot is Medplum's serverless automation primitive: bundled JavaScript triggered by Subscriptions, cron, or direct `$execute` calls. This resource manages the whole lifecycle — the Bot, its ProjectMembership (bots cannot act without one), and the deployed code. Applying a code change pushes the new bundle live to the running server; no restart is involved.

Bot code must be a single bundled JavaScript file in CommonJS shape (`exports.handler = async (medplum, event) => ...`). Multi-file TypeScript projects should be bundled with esbuild (Medplum's own workflow) and referenced via `source_path`, which keeps the bundle out of Terraform state — only its SHA-256 is stored.

The bot's runtime (`runtime_version`) is validated at plan time against the provider's `supported_bot_runtimes`, so pointing a bot at a runtime the environment cannot execute fails before anything is created.

